  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The system has converged to organisms that saturate the current solution space. Static beauty metrics and soft constraints allow local optima without real trade-offs. Plateau breaks when you: (1) add hard biomass/energy limits that force specialization, (2) expand what beauty means (temporal, relational, emergent) so no existing organism is 'beautiful' in the new dimensions, and (3) enable new interaction modalities (sensing, signaling) that create niches and strategies no previous population could express. Evolution gets stuck not because organisms are good—but because the rules have stopped rewarding novelty.; [medium] Introduce metabolic energy as a hard constraint. Organisms have fixed energy budget per generation; growth, movement, and reproduction consume energy. No organism can exceed energy budget—currently efficiency is only scored, not enforced. — Plateau indicates convergence to organisms that locally maximize the scoring formula without real trade-offs. Energy constraint forces fundamental re-optimization: organisms must choose between growth/speed/reproduction. This opens new solution space (specialist vs. generalist strategies, resource competition, niche differentiation) that hasn't been explored because soft-scoring never punished energy waste hard enough.; [medium] Expand beauty scoring to include temporal and relational dimensions: beauty-over-time (sustained coherence, rhythmic oscillation, growth arc), neighbor-based beauty (local symmetry, emergent patterns in groups, complementary shapes), and asymmetry-as-beauty (breaks current selection for simple forms). Add organism memory (one previous-timestep state variable) so behaviors can respond to history. — Current beauty likely scores static morphology (symmetry, compactness). Plateau shows static optimization exhausted. Temporal beauty and memory unlock fundamentally different strategies: organisms could evolve oscillatory behavior, protective arrangements around neighbors, or developmental sequences. These require decision functions that don't exist yet in the population.; [hard] Add two new cell types with distinct properties: sensory cells (read local gradients: neighbor density, food concentration, light) and secretory cells (emit chemicals that diffuse, affecting neighbors). Rewrite decision function to require sensory fusion (multiple inputs) rather than single-input heuristics. Organisms must now coordinate via chemical gradients. — Current organisms likely use simple if-this-then-that rules on one or two inputs. New sensory/secretory capability unlocks cooperation, signaling, and swarm-level patterns as selectable strategies. Plateau is hit because simple morphologies and simple decision rules have been optimized; adding sensory richness forces re-evolution of decision logic and enables emergent collective behavior.",
  "evidence": [
